A New Science
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, scientists gathered to think about the necessity of a new science that could be as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists believe that the fundamental questions of science have been answered.
With regard to the great challenges, it is considered that there is little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: First, the great unsolved mysteries of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), whose exploration requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Second, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and thirdly, problems whose solution must be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Darüber hinaus ist man vielerorts der Meinung, dass der einzig schwierige Teil der Arbeit darin bestünde, bereits bekannte Naturgesetze mit Hilfe neuer Technologien zum Wohle der Menschheit zu nutzen.
Wer könnte das bestreiten?
Die Modelle von heute funktionieren ja.
Eine wachsende Gruppe von Wissenschaftlern weist allerdings auf Phänomene hin, die mit den heutigen Theorien nicht so gut zu erklären sind.
Diese Probleme treten zwar immer häufiger auf, werden aber auch kunstvoll umgangen, weil es die Wissenschaft, womit diese Probleme zu erklären wären, einfach nicht gibt.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In individual scientific disciplines, knowledge is somewhat well secured.
Physics, at least the part with which we ordinary people are confronted, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – although there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet understand, it is expected that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
There are also the new social sciences, which focus on people and societies.
In each of these fields – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are established and largely beyond dispute.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest of cases is a scientist an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are so different.
This means that we cannot find answers to complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
Consider, for example, the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction occurs on the basis of physics. The information conveyed in this process is transmitted according to the laws of electricity.
Additionally, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and also transmit information in this way.
When two brains interact, a new level is added: here, the exchange of information occurs through language, symbols, and concepts.
On each level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes on each individual level.
Information is also exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this deficiency, some scientists have attempted to redefine the instruments for explaining processes within one level, in order to apply them on another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanatory patterns works quite well, but the fundamental problem remains unsolved: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the individual levels and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems in this world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this shameful lack of knowledge about how the entire system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who met in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science."
The researchers come from various countries and fields and have been working together on a decentralized basis for eight years.
In addition to scientists from the relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, language experts, and philosophers are also beginning to participate in the discussion.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," in which the scientific foundations of one level are adapted and supplemented to be applied on another level.
Others, however, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
In their view, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches will emerge from scientists who currently have no access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Nearly all activities that take place under the banner of "science" have, like their counterparts in the world of economics, developed an institutional character.
It is believed that developing countries would need to build up similar resources as industrialized countries. This could however stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas come from laboratories and research centers that are not connected to the major institutions.
The most sophisticated approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where there was a lack of computing capacity everywhere.
The most brilliant and literally world-changing insights in the field of physics in recent decades did not come, as expected, from the known innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that contributed to important insights for cognitive scientists.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (the so-called "autonomous agents") come today from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, it changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unannounced beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps were identified, for which explanations must be found.
More scientists from innovative regions will be added to this group to later identify those problems that could be solved if this new science is developed, or discovered, as one might say.

